name: seL4
description: The seL4 microkernel
interact_justification:
To obtain: see top line of https://docs.sel4.systems
To contribute: see https://sel4.systems/Contribute.html
For contact: https://sel4.systems/contact.html
contribution_justification: The main contribution guidelines are in <https://docs.sel4.systems/processes/contributing.html>, additional guidelines specific to seL4 in <https://docs.sel4.systems/projects/sel4/kernel-contribution.html>. Both are reachable from the CONTRIBUTION.md file in the repository and the main "Contribute" link on the home page at <https://sel4.systems/Contribute.html>
contribution_requirements_justification: See "Conventions" at the top of <https://docs.sel4.systems/processes/contributing.html>. The "Pull requests" link from that page also contains required tests, and formal verification.
license_location_justification: See <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/tree/master/LICENSES>.
floss_license_justification: Kernel code in the seL4 repository is licensed under GPL-2.0-only. Library code on top of the kernel under BSD-2-Clause. See also <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/blob/master/LICENSE.md> The GPL-2.0-only license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
floss_license_osi_justification: Both GPL-2.0-only and BSD-2-Clause are OSI approved. See also https://github.com/seL4/seL4/tree/master/LICENSES for the full list of things that are mentioned by any auxiliary tools and files. The GPL-2.0-only license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).
documentation_basics_justification: The sources of the reference manual are kept in <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/tree/master/manual>. There is an entire separate documentation site for seL4 at  <https://docs.sel4.systems>
documentation_interface_justification: The reference manual includes a full API description. See chapter 10 of <https://sel4.systems/Info/Docs/seL4-manual-latest.pdf>
repo_public_justification: Repository on GitHub, which provides public git repositories with URLs.
repo_track_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git can track the changes, who made them, and when they were made.
repo_interim_justification: The project repository includes the entire development history between releases.
repo_distributed_justification: Repository on GitHub, which uses git. git is distributed.
version_tags_justification: seL4 uses git tags and the GitHub release mechanism to identify releases
release_notes_justification: Release notes are posted on the seL4 website, see e.g. <https://docs.sel4.systems/releases/sel4/12.1.0>
release_notes_vulns_justification: seL4 has not any CVE assignments or similar yet, but any security improvements are identified in the release notes.
report_responses_justification: Almost all issues on <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/issues> have a response (apart from those that we use for internal tracking).
enhancement_responses_justification: Almost all issues on <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/issues> have a response. Most issues are enhancement requests or questions.
report_archive_justification: See <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/issues> for current and <https://sel4.atlassian.net/> for older issues (latter requires account, but account creation is possible for anyone).
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: The project provides a gpg key for private communication, see "Official channel" in <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/blob/master/SECURITY.md>
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: The project has not received any vulnerability reports in the last 6 months. Vulnerabilities in seL4 are extremely rare.
build_floss_tools_justification: All build tools needed for seL4 are FLOSS tools.
test_invocation_justification: The test suite uses a standard init, compile, run cycle. See e.g. <https://docs.sel4.systems/GettingStarted.html#running-sel4>
test_most_justification: The sel4test suite covers most (but not all) of the branches of seL4.
test_policy_justification: The policy for new feature testing is informal (but implied). The policy for requiring formal verification is explicit. See e.g. section on Tests in <https://docs.sel4.systems/processes/code-review.html>
tests_are_added_justification: The last releases have not included major API changes (mostly refactoring, performance improvements, build system improvements, and fixes in experimental features), but you can see reviewers requiring tests on pull requests, e.g. <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/pull/322#pullrequestreview-686920158> or <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/pull/322#issuecomment-865432029> on a pull request for an experimental feature that would be switched off by default (not yet released).
warnings_justification: The project compiles with `-Wall` and `-Werror`, see e.g. <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/blob/8afebb55a0318f68c182b270757bb29e8100f952/CMakeLists.txt#L175-L176>
warnings_fixed_justification: All compiler warnings are addressed (running on `-Werror`)
warnings_strict_justification: The project compiles with `-Wall` and `-Werror`, see e.g. <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/blob/8afebb55a0318f68c182b270757bb29e8100f952/CMakeLists.txt#L175-L176>
know_secure_design_justification: The members of the technical steering committee of the seL4 Foundation all satisfy this requirement (see <https://sel4.systems/Foundation/TSC/index.html>). Multiple of these teach secure operating systems at Universities, and/or have senior positions in companies that build secure software.
know_common_errors_justification: All members of the seL4 verification team, who produced mathematical code-level proofs (many of which are also developers) satisfy this requirement. All of the members of the technical steering committee of the seL4 Foundation also satisfy this requirement (see <https://sel4.systems/Foundation/TSC/index.html>).
crypto_published_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_call_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_floss_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_keylength_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_working_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_pfs_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_password_storage_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_random_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
delivery_mitm_justification: Assuming this is for software releases, the project uses https. Otherwise, N/A.
delivery_unsigned_justification: Assuming this is for software releases, the project uses, the project uses GitHub's release mechanism and git hashes (the kernel is usually built from source for use).
static_analysis_justification: The project does use static analysis such as Coverity, but its main static analysis is full machine-checked mathematical, code-level verification of C code base. This is the strongest form of static analysis possible, and subsumes dynamic analysis tools as well for this application. The proof scripts for seL4 are available at <https://github.com/seL4/l4v> together with instructions on how to check them separately. These proofs are run as part of CI.
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: The formal seL4 proofs cover all known common vulnerabilities such as buffer overflows, null pointer dereferences, etc. They do not (yet) cover timing side channels, but neither does any other common static analysis we are aware of.
static_analysis_fixed_justification: The formal proofs are part of CI and must pass before any code change is accepted into the kernel repository. The exception from this are experimental features that are marked as such, and unverified architecture ports, which are also marked as such.
static_analysis_often_justification: The proofs run on every commit.
dynamic_analysis_justification: The formal proofs subsume any errors that dynamic analysis tools can detect. In addition, the afl fuzzer has been run on kernel code that is not formally verified, e.g. experimental features and platform ports that are marked as unverified, but not for every release. Dynamic analysis in the form of runtime assertions for a full test suite (sel4test) is done for every commit (and release), including code that is not formally verified.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: The formal seL4 proofs guarantee the absence of any memory safety errors in C. Tests with assertions guard against potential memory safety issues such as object overlap in code that is experimental and/or not formally verified.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: Assertions are on for debug builds only and are used in development for new features or refactoring.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: All issues detected during the formal proofs are fixed before pull requests are accepted. Any issues (security, correctness, or otherwise) on code that is experimental and/or not formally verified are fixed either before pull request are accepted, or if only discovered later, fixed as soon as possible. seL4 releases typically do not contain any known security issues.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: The project currently is running CI for both tests and formal verification. See e.g. <https://sel4.systems/~bamboo/logs/RELEASE-SEL4TEST-HWTESTSGHSTATUS/1124/> for an example.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
no_leaked_credentials_justification: The project contains no private credentials.
english_justification: The main project language is English
hardening_justification: The main hardening mechanism in seL4 are the formal proofs, see <https://github.com/seL4/l4v>, but compiler flags to eliminate undefined behaviour are on by default as well.
crypto_used_network_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_tls12_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_certificate_verification_justific: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_verification_private_justificatio: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
hardened_site_justification: <https://sel4.systems> and <https://github.com/seL4/seL4> both have key hardening headers.
installation_common_justification: The kernel is not meant for installing on a system. It is usually part of a larger OS or system image.
build_reproducible_justification: The build system produces the same binaries for the same source input. See <https://docs.sel4.systems/GettingStarted#running-sel4> for build instructions and <https://github.com/seL4/seL4-CAmkES-L4v-dockerfiles> for docker images based on Debian snapshot to ensure reproducible tool chain versions.
access_continuity_justification: All members of the technical steering committee <https://sel4.systems/Foundation/TSC/> have admin access to the seL4 foundation repositories. DNS names etc are managed by the seL4 Foundation and not a single individual.
bus_factor_justification: For each main skill the bus factor in the technical steering committee is at least 3 <https://sel4.systems/Foundation/TSC/>.
documentation_architecture_justification: The seL4 white paper <https://sel4.systems/About/seL4-whitepaper.pdf> explains the kernel architecture and use model.
documentation_security_justification: The white paper contains this information: <https://sel4.systems/About/seL4-whitepaper.pdf>, as well as the FAQ <https://docs.sel4.systems/projects/sel4/frequently-asked-questions.html>
documentation_current_justification: The documentation is continuously updated with new releases, the issue tracker is used for the documentation, and API documentation is generated directly from source.
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: The project websites follow accessibility guidelines.
internationalization_justification: The kernel does not generate messages for end users. Error messages are for developers only.
sites_password_security_justification: The project does not store any user credentials.
maintenance_or_update_justification: seL4 release notes always contain update guidelines, see e.g. bottom of <https://docs.sel4.systems/releases/sel4/12.1.0>. Usually these are simple to follow. Previous versions remain available.
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio: No vulnerabilities have been reported within the last several years.
coding_standards_justification: See <https://docs.sel4.systems/processes/style-guide.html>. Style checks are part of CI and pull request acceptance.
coding_standards_enforced_justification: See <https://docs.sel4.systems/processes/code-review.html>. Style checks are part of CI and pull request acceptance.
build_standard_variables_justification: The kernel build system is designed to run as part of a larger build (this is the standard development case).
build_preserve_debug_justification: There is no installation system in the form of putting binaries somewhere in the file system. The build system generally produces an ELF image, which will honour the flags passed to the build system.
build_non_recursive_justification: The build system is not recursive.
installation_standard_variables_justific: End users are not expected to install seL4. The kernel is usually part of a larger OS or system image.
installation_development_quick_justifica: The project provides dependency description and docker images. See <https://docs.sel4.systems/projects/buildsystem/host-dependencies.html> and <https://github.com/seL4/seL4-CAmkES-L4v-dockerfiles>
external_dependencies_justification: The kernel itself does not have any external dependencies. When it is used in context, configuration control is via Google repo, for instance <https://github.com/seL4/seL4test-manifest>
dependency_monitoring_justification: The kernel does not have any external dependencies.
updateable_reused_components_justificati: The kernel does not have any external dependencies.
interfaces_current_justification: The kernel does not have any external dependencies.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: The project uses GitHub Actions <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/actions> and additional CI.
regression_tests_added50_justification: Defects are rare extremely in the verified seL4 configurations; when they occur they receive attention and tests.
test_statement_coverage80_justification: The formal proofs on seL4 subsume test coverage.
implement_secure_design_justification: seL4 does not only implement secure principles, it goes further to add a formal mathematical proof that the code satisfies high-level security properties (such as authority confinement, availability, integrity, confidentiality).
input_validation_justification: seL4 checks does not trust any user-level input
crypto_algorithm_agility_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
crypto_credential_agility_justification: seL4 does not use cryptographic mechanisms
signed_releases_justification: seL4 releases are meant for developer use only and are generally used via git directly, i.e. there is no separate release package. The git hash cryptographically identifies releases.
version_tags_signed_justification: The security of seL4 releases is assured by the ability to independently run the formal proofs directly against the sources that have been obtained.
contributors_unassociated_justification: Interpreting this as "unassociated with the Trustworthy Systems group" (who developed the kernel). Of the technical steering committee <https://sel4.systems/Foundation/TSC/index.html>, currently 5 people are members of other companies or organisations.
copyright_per_file_justification: The project uses SPDX license headers and copyright information. Checked by CI.
license_per_file_justification: The project uses SPDX license headers and copyright information. Checked by CI.
small_tasks_justification: Uses the issue badges "help wanted" and "good-first-issue" <https://github.com/seL4/seL4/labels>
secure_2FA_justification: The project uses GitHub which allows SMS verification.
test_statement_coverage90_justification: The formal proofs subsume test coverage)
test_branch_coverage80_justification: The formal proofs subsume test coverage
security_review_justification: seL4 has constant security review in the form of full formal, mathematical proofs that are continuously kept in sync with the code
assurance_case_justification: The security argument for seL4 is fully formal and machine-checked. See <https://github.com/seL4/l4v>
maintained_justification: The project is maintained by the seL4 Foundation <https://sel4.systems/Foundation.html>

report_process_justification:
The project uses the GitHub issue tracker.
The issue tracker system has pre-built templates for end users.
https://github.com/microsoft/Privileged-Security-Management/issues/new?assignees=&labels=bug&template=bug_report.md&title=Bug+Report%3A+%3CShort+Description%3E
report_responses_justification: I get emails every time an issue is filed
enhancement_responses_justification: I get emails every time an enhancement request is filed
build_common_tools_justification: Npm run script triggers TSC for typescript.
build_floss_tools_justification: Npm and TSC are both open source. No custom systems are used to build this project.
test_justification: Mocha js is the test suite and is implemented in npm run script and in the CI system.
test_invocation_justification: NPM has the test command built in to the project's script configuration.
test_most_justification: Tests are not fully implemented at the moment. Only partial code coverage is there.
test_policy_justification: All systems should be tested. This policy is definitely in place.
tests_are_added_justification: A major release has not been completed yet. Test coverage is also not complete.
warnings_fixed_justification: Code has to have 0 errors and 0 warnings to be acceptable. Partial commits may introduce warnings or errors but after all commit parts are pushed, it should be back to 0,0.
warnings_strict_justification: All warnings are not tolerated. maximum visibility is enabled where possible.
crypto_published_justification: The software does not directly implement cryptography. It uses cryptography provided by other platforms such as web servers. This software does not generate any secret material either.
crypto_keylength_justification: Azure AD handles all authentication and the Azure fabric handles encryption. The application itself does not implement crypto.
crypto_working_justification: Azure ad handles all authentication and the Azure fabric handles encryption. The application itself does not implement crypto.
crypto_pfs_justification: Azure ad handles all authentication and the Azure fabric handles encryption. The application itself does not implement crypto.
crypto_password_storage_justification: Azure AD handles all authentication and the Azure fabric handles encryption. The application itself does not implement crypto.
crypto_random_justification: Azure AD handles all authentication and the Azure fabric handles encryption. The application itself does not implement crypto.
delivery_mitm_justification: GitHub runs with HTTPS for connectivity.
delivery_unsigned_justification: GitHub runs over HTTPS for connectivity.
dynamic_analysis_justification: This is not currently implemented. This is planned for the future.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: No dynamic analysis is currently implemented.  This is planned for the future.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: No dynamic code analysis is currently implemented.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: Azure ad handles all authentication and the Azure fabric handles encryption. The application itself does not implement crypto.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: CI is implemented and integrates with the test system as well as code scanning system.
discussion_justification: GitHub supports discussions on issues and pull requests.
no_leaked_credentials_justification: All credentials are not allowed to be checked in. A code scanner runs on every commit to make sure that no creds are checked in. Also the app is desio to operate without credentials by using either environmental variables or managed identity.
hardened_site_justification: Found all required security hardening headers.
